  "prompt": "Why don't install a battery for desktop computer?",
  "response": "Desktop computers typically do not have batteries because they are designed to be stationary and plugged into a constant power source. Here are some reasons why desktop computers don't use batteries:\n\n1. Power consumption: Desktops generally require more power than laptops and have components that consume significant electricity.\n\n2. Size and design: Desktop cases are larger and not designed for portable use, so a battery would be unnecessary.\n\n3. Constant power connection: Desktops are meant to be plugged into wall outlets continuously.\n\n4. Cost: Adding a battery would increase the computer's price without providing significant benefits.\n\n5. Performance: Batteries can limit performance compared to direct electrical connection.\n\nHowever, desktop computers can use:\n- Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS) for backup power during outages\n- Internal CMOS battery to maintain BIOS settings and computer clock\n- Some specialized desktop models might have optional battery backups\n\nIf you need portable computing with battery power, laptops are the better choice.",
